body:
As far as property or constructor - suppose I have something like this:

```
public class Foo {
    private int _bar;
    public Foo(int bar) {
        _bar = bar;
    }
    public int Zerg { get { return _bar; } }
    public int bar { get; set; }
}
```

ForMember at this point doesn't make any sense - ForMember refers to destination properties, not destination constructor arguments. There's no way to affect that parameter, member maps don't apply. In the above case, there's ambiguity between the property and the constructor parameter.  Any member mappings for "bar" only get applied to the property, NOT the constructor argument.

This is why I'd tackle them separately. Internally, constructor parameter maps and property maps are modeled as two completely separate objects (ConstructorParameterMap/PropertyMap). Convenience aside - there's no guarantee that the constructor parameter and member map to the same member, NOR any guarantee that the constructor parameter is even surfaced through a member to be mapped, NOR that AutoMapper even recognizes the destination member since it will skip read-only properties.

The most obvious behavior is to treat the two separately, otherwise you're up the creek without a paddle when your destination types _internals_ don't follow some convention. That's something the dude cannot abide.
